  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">HAR TRANS/ACCOUNT &amp; REDUCING CORRUPTION</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The central objective of the project is to increase  transparency and accountability, , in State institutions and the private sector in Zimbabwe, therefore contributing to a climate in which corruption can be tackled.  To achieve this the institutions responsible for economic governance need to be scrutinized.  The reform of opaque and corrupt institutions can only be achieved if decision makers and the public have access to and are able to make appropriate use of accurate information.  The importance of information cannot be overemphasized. For the public to play their role in ensuring good economic governance the governing institutions must be generally open to public scrutiny and accountable to the public through a democratic political system.  To institutionalize accountability, permanent mechanisms must be set up to monitor the extent to which institutions are accountable, and the mechanisms must be impartial and non-political.  Where obfuscation, maladministration and malfeasance have been unearthed &#x2013; as they have in the Auditor-General&#x2019;s reports &#x2013;  permanent mechanisms must be set up to ensure implementation of recommendations for remedying them.  Illicit economic activities must be exposed. The project will work to increase public understanding of the need for transparency and accountability in order to reduce corruption, by making information available on the extent of corruption and fiscal mismanagement, by working for implementation of recommendations contained in reports dealing with corruption and mismanagement, and by seeking to strengthen laws relating to transparency, accountability and the prevention of corruption. Veritas currently monitors Parliament and issues e-bulletins on its work, analyzing existing and forthcoming legislation, and advocating and drafting reforms to the law and, if necessary, taking public interest court cases in order to promote democracy, human rights and implementation of the Constitution. The project will enhance the capacities and empowerment of civil society to effectively prevent corruption and to develop and implement evidence-based corruption prevention strategies. The project will support also the development of accountability and transparency mechanisms and strengthening of integrity of the Zimbabwe Anti-Corruption Commission through establishing a platform for cooperati on with Civil Society Organizations in order to increase citizens&#x2019; trust in governance Under the project, Veritas will extend its work: a. to uncover information on corruption and fiscal mismanagement, and to disseminate information on those topics; b. to inform the public about existing systems of financial management and improvements that should be made in those systems; c. to lobby for increased transparency and accountability; and d. to advocate changes in the law to improve governmental transparency and accountability, and to reduce the opportunities for corruption.</narrative>
  </description>
